The machine translation (MT) task is analogous to a compiler that takes source code written in one programming language and generates equivalent object code in another language. In this case, the source and target languages are human languages instead of programming languages. The MT model is trained using a supervised machine learning approach, where it learns from a large dataset of paired sentences in the source and target languages, similar to how a programmer would write equivalent functions in different programming languages. The model splits the input sentences into subword tokens, similar to how a compiler breaks down source code into individual instructions. The goal is to maximize the probability of generating the correct sequence of tokens in the target language given the source language input. The encoder can be thought of as a pre-processing step that takes the input tokens and generates an intermediate representation, similar to how a compiler generates an abstract syntax tree. The decoder then takes this representation and generates the output sentence, word by word, similar to how a compiler generates machine code from the abstract syntax tree. The training data consists of a parallel corpus, which is like a dataset of paired functions in different programming languages. To evaluate the similarity of sentences across languages, a multilingual embedding space is used, which is analogous to a unified namespace for variables and functions across different programming languages. 

